{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774643262,"nonce":"mp8HUnX3W8c2AjalGO8VSZYW9v0=","message":"Ambiguity clarification for the issue body:\n\n\"If the Jacobian eigenvalue test shows PAI-ASF only shifts the fixed point without changing eigenvalue magnitudes/angles, the network is being lazy\" — this does not specify which PAI-ASF models to test. At the time this issue was written (2026-03-23), the primary models were GRU 180-hidden, additive SISU, standard backprop, PAI-ASF, running_cost loss. However, subsequent experiments (issue 3b70482) tested the laziness hypothesis across GRU additive, GRU multiplicative, vRNN additive, and vRNN multiplicative, with both single and pop5 adversaries. The Tier 1 results (3b70482 comment #7) showed that ALL architectures and gating modes produce 0.00% SISU velocity effect, ruling out GRU-specific laziness as the explanation.\n\n\"the network is being lazy\" — \"the network\" is ambiguous. This issue was motivated by PAI-ASF models trained with standard backprop (not minimax). The subsequent minimax experiments showed the same zero SISU velocity effect, so the laziness concern extends to all training methods, not just standard backprop PAI-ASF.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}